2 !.. This subroutine computes the moisture tendencies of water vapor,
3 !.. cloud droplets, rain, cloud ice (pristine), snow, and graupel.
4 !.. Prior to WRFv2.2 this code was based on Reisner et al (1998), but
5 !.. few of those pieces remain. A complete description is now found in
6 !.. Thompson, G., P. R. Field, R. M. Rasmussen, and W. D. Hall, 2008:
7 !.. Explicit Forecasts of winter precipitation using an improved bulk
8 !.. microphysics scheme. Part II: Implementation of a new snow
9 !.. parameterization. Mon. Wea. Rev., 136, 5095-5115.
10 !.. Prior to WRFv3.1, this code was single-moment rain prediction as
11 !.. described in the reference above, but in v3.1 and higher, the
12 !.. scheme is two-moment rain (predicted rain number concentration).
13 !..
14 !.. Most importantly, users may wish to modify the prescribed number of
15 !.. cloud droplets (Nt_c; see guidelines mentioned below). Otherwise,
16 !.. users may alter the rain and graupel size distribution parameters
17 !.. to use exponential (Marshal-Palmer) or generalized gamma shape.
18 !.. The snow field assumes a combination of two gamma functions (from
19 !.. Field et al. 2005) and would require significant modifications
20 !.. throughout the entire code to alter its shape as well as accretion
21 !.. rates. Users may also alter the constants used for density of rain,
22 !.. graupel, ice, and snow, but the latter is not constant when using
23 !.. Paul Field's snow distribution and moments methods. Other values
24 !.. users can modify include the constants for mass and/or velocity
25 !.. power law relations and assumed capacitances used in deposition/
26 !.. sublimation/evaporation/melting.
27 !.. Remaining values should probably be left alone.
28 !..
29 !..Author: Greg Thompson, NCAR-RAL, gthompsn@ucar.edu, 303-497-2805
30 !..Last modified: 27 Jul 2012
31 !+---+-----------------------------------------------------------------+
32 !wrft:model_layer:physics
33 !+---+-----------------------------------------------------------------+
34 !

63 !.. N(D) = N_0 * D**mu * exp(-lamda*D); mu=0 is exponential.
64 REAL, PARAMETER, PRIVATE:: mu_r = 0.0

70 !..Sum of two gamma distrib for snow (Field et al. 2005).
71 !.. N(D) = M2**4/M3**3 * [Kap0*exp(-M2*Lam0*D/M3)
72 !.. + Kap1*(M2/M3)**mu_s * D**mu_s * exp(-M2*Lam1*D/M3)]
73 !.. M2 and M3 are the (bm_s)th and (bm_s+1)th moments respectively
74 !.. calculated as function of ice water content and temperature.
75 REAL, PARAMETER, PRIVATE:: mu_s = 0.6357
76 REAL, PARAMETER, PRIVATE:: Kap0 = 490.6
77 REAL, PARAMETER, PRIVATE:: Kap1 = 17.46
78 REAL, PARAMETER, PRIVATE:: Lam0 = 20.78
79 REAL, PARAMETER, PRIVATE:: Lam1 = 3.29
80
81 !..Y-intercept parameter for graupel is not constant and depends on

83 !.. y-intercept for an exponential distrib and proper values are
84 !.. computed based on same mixing ratio and total number concentration.

2409 b_ = sb(1)+ sb(2)*tc0 + sb(3)*cse(1) + sb(4)*tc0*cse(1) &
2410 + sb(5)*tc0*tc0 + sb(6)*cse(1)*cse(1) &
2411 + sb(7)*tc0*tc0*cse(1) + sb(8)*tc0*cse(1)*cse(1) &
2412 ✗ + sb(9)*tc0*tc0*tc0 + sb(10)*cse(1)*cse(1)*cse(1)
2413 ✗ smoc(k) = a_ * smo2(k)**b_
2414
2415 !..Calculate bm_s+bv_s (th) moment. Useful for sedimentation.
2416 loga_ = sa(1) + sa(2)*tc0 + sa(3)*cse(14) &
2417 + sa(4)*tc0*cse(14) + sa(5)*tc0*tc0 &
2418 + sa(6)*cse(14)*cse(14) + sa(7)*tc0*tc0*cse(14) &
2419 + sa(8)*tc0*cse(14)*cse(14) + sa(9)*tc0*tc0*tc0 &
2420 ✗ + sa(10)*cse(14)*cse(14)*cse(14)
2421 ✗ a_ = 10.0**loga_
2422 b_ = sb(1)+ sb(2)*tc0 + sb(3)*cse(14) + sb(4)*tc0*cse(14) &
2423 + sb(5)*tc0*tc0 + sb(6)*cse(14)*cse(14) &
2424 + sb(7)*tc0*tc0*cse(14) + sb(8)*tc0*cse(14)*cse(14) &
2425 ✗ + sb(9)*tc0*tc0*tc0 + sb(10)*cse(14)*cse(14)*cse(14)
2426 ✗ smod(k) = a_ * smo2(k)**b_
2427 enddo

2429 !+---+-----------------------------------------------------------------+
2430 !..Calculate y-intercept, slope values for graupel.
2431 !+---+-----------------------------------------------------------------+
2432 ✗ N0_min = gonv_max
2433 ✗ do k = kte, kts, -1
2434 ✗ if (temp(k).lt.270.65 .and. L_qr(k) .and. mvd_r(k).gt.100.E-6) then
2435 ✗ xslw1 = 4.01 + alog10(mvd_r(k))
2436 else
2437 ✗ xslw1 = 0.01
2438 endif
2439 ✗ ygra1 = 4.31 + alog10(max(5.E-5, rg(k)))
2440 ✗ zans1 = 3.1 + (100./(300.*xslw1*ygra1/(10./xslw1+1.+0.25*ygra1)+30.+10.*ygra1))
2441 ✗ N0_exp = 10.**(zans1)
2442 ✗ N0_exp = MAX(DBLE(gonv_min), MIN(N0_exp, DBLE(gonv_max)))
2443 ✗ N0_min = MIN(N0_exp, N0_min)
2444 ✗ N0_exp = N0_min
2445 ✗ lam_exp = (N0_exp*am_g*cgg(1)/rg(k))**oge1
2446 ✗ lamg = lam_exp * (cgg(3)*ogg2*ogg1)**obmg
2447 ✗ ilamg(k) = 1./lamg
2448 ✗ N0_g(k) = N0_exp/(cgg(2)*lam_exp) * lamg**cge(2)
2449 enddo
2450
2451 endif

2453 !+---+-----------------------------------------------------------------+
2454 !..Calculate y-intercept, slope values for rain.
2455 !+---+-----------------------------------------------------------------+
2456 ✗ do k = kte, kts, -1
2457 ✗ lamr = (am_r*crg(3)*org2*nr(k)/rr(k))**obmr
2458 ✗ ilamr(k) = 1./lamr
2459 ✗ mvd_r(k) = (3.0 + mu_r + 0.672) / lamr
2460 ✗ N0_r(k) = nr(k)*org2*lamr**cre(2)
2461 enddo

2463 !+---+-----------------------------------------------------------------+
2464 !..Cloud water condensation and evaporation. Newly formulated using
2465 !.. Newton-Raphson iterations (3 should suffice) as provided by B. Hall.
2466 !+---+-----------------------------------------------------------------+
2467 ✗ do k = kts, kte
2468 ✗ if ( (ssatw(k).gt. eps) .or. (ssatw(k).lt. -eps .and. &
2469 ✗ L_qc(k)) ) then
2470 ✗ clap = (qv(k)-qvs(k))/(1. + lvt2(k)*qvs(k))
2471 ✗ do n = 1, 3
2472 ✗ fcd = qvs(k)* EXP(lvt2(k)*clap) - qv(k) + clap
2473 ✗ dfcd = qvs(k)*lvt2(k)* EXP(lvt2(k)*clap) + 1.
2474 ✗ clap = clap - fcd/dfcd
2475 enddo
2476 ✗ xrc = rc(k) + clap * rho(k)
2477 ✗ if (xrc.gt. 0.0) then
2478 ✗ prw_vcd(k) = clap*odt
2479 else
2480 ✗ prw_vcd(k) = -rc(k)/rho(k)*odts
2481 endif
2482
2483 ✗ qcten(k) = qcten(k) + prw_vcd(k)
2484 ✗ qvten(k) = qvten(k) - prw_vcd(k)
2485 ✗ tten(k) = tten(k) + lvap(k)*ocp(k)*prw_vcd(k)*(1-IFDRY)
2486 ✗ rc(k) = MAX(R1, (qc1d(k) + DT*qcten(k))*rho(k))
2487 ✗ qv(k) = MAX(1.E-10, qv1d(k) + DT*qvten(k))
2488 ✗ temp(k) = t1d(k) + DT*tten(k)
2489 ✗ rho(k) = 0.622*pres(k)/(R*temp(k)*(qv(k)+0.622))
2490 ✗ qvs(k) = rslf(pres(k), temp(k))
2491 ✗ ssatw(k) = qv(k)/qvs(k) - 1.
2492 endif
2493 enddo

2495 !+---+-----------------------------------------------------------------+
2496 !.. If still subsaturated, allow rain to evaporate, following
2497 !.. Srivastava & Coen (1992).
2498 !+---+-----------------------------------------------------------------+
2499 ✗ do k = kts, kte
2500 ✗ if ( (ssatw(k).lt. -eps) .and. L_qr(k) &
2501 ✗ .and. (.not.(prw_vcd(k).gt. 0.)) ) then
2502 ✗ tempc = temp(k) - 273.15
2503 ✗ otemp = 1./temp(k)
2504 ✗ rhof(k) = SQRT(RHO_NOT/rho(k))
2505 ✗ rhof2(k) = SQRT(rhof(k))
2506 ✗ diffu(k) = 2.11E-5*(temp(k)/273.15)**1.94 * (101325./pres(k))
2507 ✗ if (tempc .ge. 0.0) then
2508 ✗ visco(k) = (1.718+0.0049*tempc)*1.0E-5
2509 else
2510 ✗ visco(k) = (1.718+0.0049*tempc-1.2E-5*tempc*tempc)*1.0E-5
2511 endif
2512 ✗ vsc2(k) = SQRT(rho(k)/visco(k))
2513 ✗ lvap(k) = lvap0 + (2106.0 - 4218.0)*tempc
2514 ✗ tcond(k) = (5.69 + 0.0168*tempc)*1.0E-5 * 418.936
2515 ✗ ocp(k) = 1./(Cp*(1.+0.887*qv(k)))
2516
2517 ✗ rvs = rho(k)*qvs(k)
2518 ✗ rvs_p = rvs*otemp*(lvap(k)*otemp*oRv - 1.)
2519 ✗ rvs_pp = rvs * ( otemp*(lvap(k)*otemp*oRv - 1.) &
2520 ✗ *otemp*(lvap(k)*otemp*oRv - 1.) &
2521 ✗ + (-2.*lvap(k)*otemp*otemp*otemp*oRv) &
2522 ✗ + otemp*otemp)
2523 ✗ gamsc = lvap(k)*diffu(k)/tcond(k) * rvs_p
2524 alphsc = 0.5*(gamsc/(1.+gamsc))*(gamsc/(1.+gamsc)) &
2525 ✗ * rvs_pp/rvs_p * rvs/rvs_p
2526 ✗ alphsc = MAX(1.E-9, alphsc)
2527 ✗ xsat = MIN(-1.E-9, ssatw(k))
2528 t1_evap = 2.*PI*( 1.0 - alphsc*xsat &
2529 + 2.*alphsc*alphsc*xsat*xsat &
2530 - 5.*alphsc*alphsc*alphsc*xsat*xsat*xsat ) &
2531 ✗ / (1.+gamsc)
2532
2533 ✗ lamr = 1./ilamr(k)
2534 !..Rapidly eliminate near zero values when low humidity (<95%)
2535 ✗ if (qv(k)/qvs(k) .lt. 0.95 .AND. rr(k)/rho(k).le.1.E-8) then
2536 ✗ prv_rev(k) = rr(k)/rho(k)*odts
2537 else
2538 ✗ prv_rev(k) = t1_evap*diffu(k)*(-ssatw(k))*N0_r(k)*rvs &
2539 ✗ * (t1_qr_ev*ilamr(k)**cre(10) &
2540 ✗ + t2_qr_ev*vsc2(k)*rhof2(k)*((lamr+0.5*fv_r)**(-cre(11))))
2541 ✗ rate_max = MIN((rr(k)/rho(k)*odts), (qvs(k)-qv(k))*odts)
2542 ✗ prv_rev(k) = MIN(DBLE(rate_max), prv_rev(k)/rho(k))
2543 endif
2544 ✗ pnr_rev(k) = MIN(DBLE(nr(k)*0.99/rho(k)*odts), & ! RAIN2M
2545 ✗ prv_rev(k) * nr(k)/rr(k))
2546
2547 ✗ qrten(k) = qrten(k) - prv_rev(k)
2548 ✗ qvten(k) = qvten(k) + prv_rev(k)
2549 ✗ nrten(k) = nrten(k) - pnr_rev(k)
2550 ✗ tten(k) = tten(k) - lvap(k)*ocp(k)*prv_rev(k)*(1-IFDRY)
2551
2552 ✗ rr(k) = MAX(R1, (qr1d(k) + DT*qrten(k))*rho(k))
2553 ✗ qv(k) = MAX(1.E-10, qv1d(k) + DT*qvten(k))
2554 ✗ nr(k) = MAX(R2, (nr1d(k) + DT*nrten(k))*rho(k))
2555 ✗ temp(k) = t1d(k) + DT*tten(k)
2556 ✗ rho(k) = 0.622*pres(k)/(R*temp(k)*(qv(k)+0.622))
2557 endif
2558 enddo

2560 ! do k = kts, kte
2561 ! evapprod(k) = prv_rev(k) - (min(zeroD0,prs_sde(k)) + &
2562 ! min(zeroD0,prg_gde(k)))

3217 !..This is a literal adaptation of Bigg (1954) probability of drops of

3317 !..Cloud ice converting to snow since portion greater than min snow
3318 !.. size. Given cloud ice content (kg/m**3), number concentration
3319 !.. (#/m**3) and gamma shape parameter, mu_i, break the distrib into
3320 !.. bins and figure out the mass/number of ice with sizes larger than
3321 !.. D0s. Also, compute incomplete gamma function for the integration
3322 !.. of ice depositional growth from diameter=0 to D0s. Amount of
3323 !.. ice depositional growth is this portion of distrib while larger
3324 !.. diameters contribute to snow growth (as in Harrington et al. 1995).
3325 !+---+-----------------------------------------------------------------+
3326
3327 ✗ subroutine qi_aut_qs
3328
3329 implicit none
3330
3331 !..Local variables
3332 ✗ INTEGER:: i, j, n2
3333 ✗ DOUBLE PRECISION, DIMENSION(nbi):: N_i
3334 ✗ DOUBLE PRECISION:: N0_i, lami, Di_mean, t1, t2
3335 ✗ REAL:: xlimit_intg
3336
3337 !+---+
3338
3339 ✗ do j = 1, ntb_i1
3340 ✗ do i = 1, ntb_i
3341 ✗ lami = (am_i*cig(2)*oig1*Nt_i(j)/r_i(i))**obmi
3342 ✗ Di_mean = (bm_i + mu_i + 1.) / lami
3343 ✗ N0_i = Nt_i(j)*oig1 * lami**cie(1)
3344 ✗ t1 = 0.0d0
3345 ✗ t2 = 0.0d0
3346 ✗ if (SNGL(Di_mean) .gt. 5.*D0s) then
3347 ✗ t1 = r_i(i)
3348 ✗ t2 = Nt_i(j)
3349 ✗ tpi_ide(i,j) = 0.0D0
3350 ✗ elseif (SNGL(Di_mean) .lt. D0i) then
3351 ✗ t1 = 0.0D0
3352 ✗ t2 = 0.0D0
3353 ✗ tpi_ide(i,j) = 1.0D0
3354 else
3355 ✗ xlimit_intg = lami*D0s
3356 ✗ tpi_ide(i,j) = GAMMP(mu_i+2.0, xlimit_intg) * 1.0D0
3357 ✗ do n2 = 1, nbi
3358 ✗ N_i(n2) = N0_i*Di(n2)**mu_i * DEXP(-lami*Di(n2))*dti(n2)
3359 ✗ if (Di(n2).ge.D0s) then
3360 ✗ t1 = t1 + N_i(n2) * am_i*Di(n2)**bm_i
3361 ✗ t2 = t2 + N_i(n2)
3362 endif
3363 enddo
3364 endif
3365 ✗ tps_iaus(i,j) = t1
3366 ✗ tni_iaus(i,j) = t2
3367 enddo
3368 enddo

3373 !..Variable collision efficiency for rain collecting cloud water using

3378 ✗ subroutine table_Efrw
3379
3380 implicit none
3381
3382 !..Local variables
3383 ✗ DOUBLE PRECISION:: vtr, stokes, reynolds, Ef_rw
3384 ✗ DOUBLE PRECISION:: p, yc0, F, G, H, z, K0, X
3385 ✗ INTEGER:: i, j
3386
3387 ✗ do j = 1, nbc
3388 ✗ do i = 1, nbr
3389 ✗ Ef_rw = 0.0
3390 ✗ p = Dc(j)/Dr(i)
3391 ✗ if (Dr(i).lt.50.E-6 .or. Dc(j).lt.3.E-6) then
3392 ✗ t_Efrw(i,j) = 0.0
3393 ✗ elseif (p.gt.0.25) then
3394 ✗ X = Dc(j)*1.D6
3395 ✗ if (Dr(i) .lt. 75.e-6) then
3396 ✗ Ef_rw = 0.026794*X - 0.20604
3397 ✗ elseif (Dr(i) .lt. 125.e-6) then
3398 ✗ Ef_rw = -0.00066842*X*X + 0.061542*X - 0.37089
3399 ✗ elseif (Dr(i) .lt. 175.e-6) then
3400 Ef_rw = 4.091e-06*X*X*X*X - 0.00030908*X*X*X &
3401 ✗ + 0.0066237*X*X - 0.0013687*X - 0.073022
3402 ✗ elseif (Dr(i) .lt. 250.e-6) then
3403 Ef_rw = 9.6719e-5*X*X*X - 0.0068901*X*X + 0.17305*X &
3404 ✗ - 0.65988
3405 ✗ elseif (Dr(i) .lt. 350.e-6) then
3406 Ef_rw = 9.0488e-5*X*X*X - 0.006585*X*X + 0.16606*X &
3407 ✗ - 0.56125
3408 else
3409 Ef_rw = 0.00010721*X*X*X - 0.0072962*X*X + 0.1704*X &
3410 ✗ - 0.46929
3411 endif
3412 else
3413 ✗ vtr = -0.1021 + 4.932E3*Dr(i) - 0.9551E6*Dr(i)*Dr(i) &
3414 ✗ + 0.07934E9*Dr(i)*Dr(i)*Dr(i) &
3415 ✗ - 0.002362E12*Dr(i)*Dr(i)*Dr(i)*Dr(i)
3416 ✗ stokes = Dc(j)*Dc(j)*vtr*rho_w/(9.*1.718E-5*Dr(i))
3417 ✗ reynolds = 9.*stokes/(p*p*rho_w)
3418
3419 ✗ F = DLOG(reynolds)
3420 ✗ G = -0.1007D0 - 0.358D0*F + 0.0261D0*F*F
3421 ✗ K0 = DEXP(G)
3422 ✗ z = DLOG(stokes/(K0+1.D-15))
3423 ✗ H = 0.1465D0 + 1.302D0*z - 0.607D0*z*z + 0.293D0*z*z*z
3424 ✗ yc0 = 2.0D0/PI * ATAN(H)
3425 ✗ Ef_rw = (yc0+p)*(yc0+p) / ((1.+p)*(1.+p))
3426
3427 endif
3428
3429 ✗ t_Efrw(i,j) = MAX(0.0, MIN(SNGL(Ef_rw), 0.95))

3550 ✗ SUBROUTINE GCF(GAMMCF,A,X,GLN)
3551 ! --- RETURNS THE INCOMPLETE GAMMA FUNCTION Q(A,X) EVALUATED BY ITS
3552 ! --- CONTINUED FRACTION REPRESENTATION AS GAMMCF. ALSO RETURNS
3553 ! --- LN(GAMMA(A)) AS GLN. THE CONTINUED FRACTION IS EVALUATED BY
3554 ! --- A MODIFIED LENTZ METHOD.
3555 ! --- USES GAMMLN
3556 IMPLICIT NONE
3557 INTEGER, PARAMETER:: ITMAX=100
3558 REAL, PARAMETER:: gEPS=3.E-7
3559 REAL, PARAMETER:: FPMIN=1.E-30
3560 REAL, INTENT(IN):: A, X
3561 REAL:: GAMMCF,GLN
3562 ✗ INTEGER:: I
3563 ✗ REAL:: AN,B,C,D,DEL,H
3564 ✗ GLN=GAMMLN(A)
3565 ✗ B=X+1.-A
3566 ✗ C=1./FPMIN
3567 ✗ D=1./B
3568 ✗ H=D
3569 ✗ DO 11 I=1,ITMAX
3570 ✗ AN=-I*(I-A)
3571 ✗ B=B+2.
3572 ✗ D=AN*D+B
3573 ✗ IF(ABS(D).LT.FPMIN)D=FPMIN
3574 ✗ C=B+AN/C
3575 ✗ IF(ABS(C).LT.FPMIN)C=FPMIN
3576 ✗ D=1./D
3577 ✗ DEL=D*C
3578 ✗ H=H*DEL
3579 ✗ IF(ABS(DEL-1.).LT.gEPS)GOTO 1
3580 ✗ 11 CONTINUE
3581 ✗ PRINT *, 'A TOO LARGE, ITMAX TOO SMALL IN GCF'
3582 ✗ 1 GAMMCF=EXP(-X+A*LOG(X)-GLN)*H
3583 ✗ END SUBROUTINE GCF

3590 ! --- USES GAMMLN
3591 IMPLICIT NONE

3597 ✗ REAL:: AP,DEL,SUM
3598 ✗ GLN=GAMMLN(A)

3600 ✗ IF(X.LT.0.) PRINT *, 'X < 0 IN GSER'
